rofound self-awareness, where language acts as a bridge between his internal world and the external realities he faces. This interplay between language and selfhood is a central motif that resonates throughout the text, making it a rich subject for literary and sociolinguistic analysis.</p>\n<h3>The Role of Language as a Tool for Empowerment</h3>\n<p>Language, in Baca’s narrative, is not merely a means of communication; it is a vehicle for reclaiming agency and identity. Coming into language by Jimmy Santiago Baca illustrates how literacy and poetic expression enabled him to transcend the limitations imposed by his environment. By learning to articulate his experiences, Baca challenged the narratives that had previously defined him—those of criminality and marginalization.</p>\n<p>This theme aligns with broader discussions in sociolinguistics about language as a form of power. Baca’s story exemplifies how marginalized individuals can harness language to resist dominant discourses and assert their presence in society. His transformation underscores the importance of educational and rehabilitative programs that emphasize language skills for incarcerated populations.</p>\n<h3>Poetry as a Healing Mechanism</h3>\n<p>Another critical aspect of *Coming into Language* is the therapeutic role that poetry played in Baca’s life. The act of writing poetry allowed him to process trauma, confront his past, and envision a different future. This function of poetry as a form of emotional and psychological healing is well-documented in literary therapy studies, and Baca’s personal account provides a powerful case study.</p>\n<p>His poetry, which often draws on Chicano cultural themes and imagery, serves as a medium through which he connects with his heritage and community. This cultural reclamation through language highlights the intersection of personal and collective identity formation, a theme that enriches the interpretive layers of his work.</p>\n<h2>Contextualizing Coming into 